### Description

Hi!
In an `nx` workspace I have an Angular v19 application and a buildable library that uses `@nx/angular:ng-packagr-lite`. The problem I am encountering is the following.
If I start the application in development mode everything works as it should.

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/95289e8f-86cc-4717-a883-c8e1e3d3df76)

As you can see in the image above, the style is applied correctly.

However, if I build the app in production, the style is not applied because it has the wrong CSS selectors.

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/f4f02c1a-26ac-4440-af18-6d725e783278)


As you can see in the image above, it creates an incorrect CSS rule. The pseudo class [:is()](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/:is) has no selectors in it and it targets `ngcontent` instead of `nghost`.
The `child` component it's dynamically created within the group component and indeed uses `<ng-content>`. However, there is no `ngcontent` attribute applied on the HTML elements.

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/c316a71f-51fb-4199-88d4-48148042fff7)

The code of the `app.component.ts` is the following:
```ts
@Component({
  selector: 'my-app-root',
  template: ` <ng-container #contentTpl /> `,
  changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush
})
export class AppComponent implements OnInit {
  @ViewChild('contentTpl', { read: ViewContainerRef, static: true }) content!: ViewContainerRef;

  ngOnInit() {
    const projectedGroup = this.content.createComponent(ChildComponent);

    this.content.createComponent(MyGroupComponent, {
      projectableNodes: [[projectedGroup.location.nativeElement]]
    });
  }
}
```

I provided a link to a repo where this can be reproduced.

Run `npm ci` to install the dependencies and then `npm run start -- my-app` to start in develop and `docker compose up -d` to build it in production. If you don't have docker, then run `npm run build -- my-app` and either serve the static files in the `dist` folder with a server or inspect the `main.*.js` file and look for `border: 10px solid orange`. You will see the following `:is() > *[_ngcontent-%COMP%]{border:10px solid orange}`

