### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

router

### Description

Currently, the implementation of `<router-outlet>` in Angular doesn't optimally handle the need for multiple named outlets at the same level when one or more sub-features are attached to the view a variable number of times (0 to n).

The issue I'm facing is related to how Angular's Dependency Injection works. Each sub-feature, whether static or dynamic, requires its own instances of the providers. To ensure this, I need a distinct `<router-outlet>` for each sub-feature so that the component attached there can access its parent component's providers.

Providing these providers via the route configuration is not feasible because the instances need to be tied to the lifecycle of the parent component:
=> The providers must be destroyed along with their parent component.
=> The providers must be re-initialized when their parent component is initialized.

### Example:
```html
<app-feature-page>
  <app-static-sub-feature> <!-- declared in its own @Component({ providers: [...] }) -->
    <router-outlet name="staticSubFeature" />
  </app-static-sub-feature>

  @for (item of items; track item.id) {
    <app-dynamic-sub-feature> <!-- declared in its own @Component({ providers: [...] }) -->
      <router-outlet name="dynamicSubFeature-{{ item.id }}" />
    </app-dynamic-sub-feature>
  }
</app-feature-page>
```
> This example is intentionally simplified to illustrate the problem. I can provide a more concrete use case if needed.

The core issue lies in the route configuration. While it's possible to have a dynamic `name` attribute in the HTML template, this doesn't work at the route configuration level:
```ts
export const routes: Routes = [
  // ... other routes ...
  { path: '...', outlet: 'dynamicSubFeature-xxx' } // <= No way to tell Angular how to retrieve a dynamically named outlet
];
```

#### Angular doesn't provide a mechanism to define route targets for dynamically named `<router-outlet>`s in the route configuration. This prevents proper routing to `<router-outlet>`s that are created dynamically in the template.

### Current Workaround and its Drawbacks:

Currently, to achieve the desired behavior of conditionally displaying components within dynamically generated sub-features while maintaining distinct provider scopes, I've implemented a workaround using `*ngComponentOutlet` and query parameters.

Instead of relying on named `<router-outlet>`s and path-based routing for the sub-feature components, I dynamically render components using `*ngComponentOutlet` based on a query parameter:
```ts
@Component({
    ....,
    providers: [Foo, Bar] // <= the providers used by either/both this component or/and its sub components, etc.
    template: `
        ....
        @if (displaySubFeatureSubComponent$ | async) {
            <ng-container *ngComponentOutlet="SubFeatureSubComponent" />
        }
    `,
})
export class SubFeature {
    protected readonly SubFeatureSubComponenp = SubFeatureSubComponent;

    readonly id = input.required<string>();

    private readonly activatedRoute = inject(ActivatedRoute);
    protected readonly displaySubFeatureSubComponent$ = this.activatedRoute.queryParamMap().pipe(
        map((queryParams) => queryParams.get('subfeature') === this.id()) // instead of { path: 'subfeature/:id' }
    );
}
```

This approach involves:
- Replacing `<router-outlet>` within each sub-feature with `<ng-container *ngComponentOutlet="...">`
- Instead of defining routes with specific paths for sub-components, the display of these components is controlled by a query parameter (e.g., `?subfeature=someId`)
- The `displaySubFeatureSubComponent$` observable checks the query parameter against the sub-feature's ID to determine whether to render the sub-component.

While this workaround functions as expected in terms of achieving isolated provider instances and conditional rendering, it is **unconventional and introduces several drawbacks** like the loss of standard routing semantics: It deviates from the standard Angular routing paradigm, making the application's navigation logic less intuitive and harder to understand for new developers on the project

### Proposed solution

To address the limitation of targeting dynamically named `<router-outlet>`s, I propose enhancing the `Route['outlet']` configuration to support regular expressions or a dedicated pattern-matching syntax. This would enable developers to define route targets that can match outlet names based on a defined pattern.

One potential implementation involves allowing a `RegExp` object to be assigned to the outlet property in the route configuration:
```ts
const routes: Routes = [
  // ... other routes ...
  { path: '...', outlet: /^dynamicSubFeature-\d+$/ }
];
```

In the template, the dynamic outlet would be set like this:
```html
<a [routerLink]="['', { outlets: { [`dynamicSubFeature-${id}`]: [''] } }]">...</a>

<router-outlet name="dynamicSubFeature-{{id}}" />
```

My initial investigation of the Angular Router's source code suggests that this approach is technically feasible with relatively minor modifications. Specifically, the [`getOutlet` and `sortByMatchingOutlets` methods](https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/main/packages%2Frouter%2Fsrc%2Futils%2Fconfig.ts#L225-L237) could be adapted to handle RegExp objects:
```diff
export function getOutlet(route: Route): RegExp {
- return route.outlet || PRIMARY_OUTLET;
+ const outlet = route.outlet || PRIMARY_OUTLET;
+ return typeof outlet === 'string' ? RegExp(outlet) : outlet;
}

export function sortByMatchingOutlets(routes: Routes, outletName: string): Routes {
- const sortedConfig = routes.filter((r) => getOutlet(r) === outletName);
+ const sortedConfig = routes.filter((r) => getOutlet(r).test(outletName));
- sortedConfig.push(...routes.filter((r) => getOutlet(r) !== outletName));
+ sortedConfig.push(...routes.filter((r) => !getOutlet(r).test(outletName)));
  return sortedConfig;
}
```

### Alternatives considered

While using `RegExp` is my initial thought, other approaches could be considered:

- Special Syntax: Introducing a specific syntax within the outlet string (similar to path wildcards or parameters) to define patterns. For example: `'dynamicSubFeature-*'`, `'dynamicSubFeature-{id}'`.
- Dedicated identifier Key: Adding a new identifier key to the Route configuration specifically for matching dynamic outlet names. This could potentially leverage the `@for` `track` expression's logic or a similar mechanism.

